WEBVTT

00:03.592 --> 00:04.954
I'm putting this on, OK?

00:06.075 --> 00:09.299
We're with Mr. Dave Kirshenbaum in New York at the Carnegie Bookshop.

00:09.319 --> 00:10.660
I just want to identify the tape.

00:10.680 --> 00:15.706
And you just told me you have a catalog of George D. Smith when he was selling things for $2.

00:15.846 --> 00:31.624
How you doing?

00:31.644 --> 00:32.265
David Redden?

00:32.414 --> 00:33.936
Yeah, I'm going to give it to David.

00:34.777 --> 00:35.257
Well, you know what?

00:35.297 --> 00:37.520
You could loan it to me, and I'll give it back to you.

00:39.121 --> 00:39.722
Sadler.

00:40.283 --> 00:42.185
I have that Sadler set over there.

00:42.205 --> 00:43.286
I've got to shut this off later.

00:44.707 --> 00:48.492
Well, anyway, you said that you may well be the only person alive.

00:48.612 --> 00:49.653
Well, I don't know of anybody.

00:49.673 --> 00:50.414
But it's possible.

00:50.794 --> 00:51.835
I don't know of anybody.

00:51.995 --> 00:52.796
I don't remember.

00:53.577 --> 00:54.838
I don't remember anybody.

00:54.919 --> 00:56.360
Did you attend as a bookman?

00:56.841 --> 00:57.081
Yes.

00:58.142 --> 01:00.885
And so were you there bidding and...

01:01.169 --> 01:02.831
Hoping to bid or buy?

01:03.092 --> 01:04.474
That's right.

01:04.494 --> 01:05.335
How old were you then?

01:06.236 --> 01:08.419
Well, I was born in 95.

01:08.660 --> 01:13.046
I'll be 95 January 5.

01:14.929 --> 01:16.331
God bless you.

01:18.414 --> 01:18.774
I had your energy.

01:18.794 --> 01:19.636
What's your secret?

01:20.577 --> 01:21.739
Is there a secret to this?

01:22.139 --> 01:24.302
No secret.

01:24.322 --> 01:25.544
I've been in this business.

01:25.624 --> 01:28.408
I opened in 1910.

01:28.508 --> 01:29.129
Here in New York?

01:29.169 --> 01:29.590
In New York.

01:30.380 --> 01:42.611
I've been in New York ever since, and I've attended every important sale, any sale as a matter of fact, important and non-important.

01:42.631 --> 01:48.196
Would you say that you do most of your acquiring at options, or do you also do private advertising?

01:48.216 --> 01:48.397
No, no.

01:48.417 --> 01:50.118
Years ago, I used to buy big libraries.

01:50.138 --> 01:52.641
You see, I had a very big place, I have to tell you.

01:53.301 --> 01:59.627
I now dwindle down to doing specifics only.

02:00.907 --> 02:02.288
I had a very big place.

02:02.369 --> 02:06.533
I had a place twenty times, forty times the size.

02:07.854 --> 02:11.158
Must have had two, three hundred thousand books.

02:11.658 --> 02:12.899
Wow.

02:12.919 --> 02:15.742
And I was there for 59th Street.

02:15.862 --> 02:17.444
I was there for fifty years.

02:17.764 --> 02:19.686
Was it also called the Carnegie Bookshop?

02:19.706 --> 02:19.867
Yeah.

02:20.928 --> 02:24.972
Has it always been called the Carnegie Bookshop, your business?

02:24.992 --> 02:25.092
Yes.

02:26.827 --> 02:29.451
And you said you used to buy entire libraries.

02:29.491 --> 02:31.193
I used to buy entire libraries, yes.

02:31.594 --> 02:33.456
And I'd buy at auction.

02:34.177 --> 02:35.599
I'd buy for customers.

02:36.701 --> 02:41.047
You, as I understand it, were extremely friendly with Bradley Martin.

02:41.167 --> 02:41.888
Very friendly.

02:42.008 --> 02:45.153
For fifty years, I used to see him.

02:45.393 --> 02:48.557
I had lunch with him two or three times a week.

02:48.637 --> 02:52.503
Were you largely responsible for building his library?

02:52.603 --> 02:54.105
A great many of the things.

02:54.205 --> 02:55.467
He bought all over the world.

02:56.493 --> 03:01.659
Would you judge him as one of the great book collectors of your lifetime?

03:01.679 --> 03:02.100
No question about it.

03:03.882 --> 03:10.510
In terms of not only the quality of the collection, but also what other qualities would you say?

03:10.530 --> 03:20.002
Well, first of all, he was particular about condition.

03:20.022 --> 03:25.068
And if he didn't want a thing, no matter what it was, he wouldn't buy it.

03:25.088 --> 03:25.909
And if he'd want it,

03:27.307 --> 03:30.152
And he'd show him something, he'd sit right here where you're sitting.

03:30.653 --> 03:31.915
And I would show him something.

03:32.516 --> 03:38.406
No matter what I'd say, he'd take out his wallet, write a check right, sit down.

03:38.426 --> 03:48.083
Was he the kind of collector who, and as we talk about Bradley Martin, I'm looking at his catalogs, the catalogs of his books over there, yeah, because I know the books.

03:48.103 --> 03:50.407
He is one collector who really knew his books.

03:50.607 --> 03:52.470
Oh, yes.

03:52.585 --> 03:55.810
I'm sure there are collectors who don't even know half of the things that they have.

03:55.910 --> 03:57.832
That's an accumulator.

03:58.153 --> 03:59.495
That's not a collector.

03:59.515 --> 04:01.638
Maybe you can define the difference for me.

04:02.359 --> 04:05.303
Could you characterize one from the other?

04:05.383 --> 04:07.466
There are some people that are accumulators.

04:07.867 --> 04:10.170
They'll take anything.

04:10.190 --> 04:15.938
But there are some people that are very careful with what they eat.

04:17.100 --> 04:18.762
You've got to give them certain things.

04:19.670 --> 04:23.134
Were you disappointed that the Martin Collection was sold?

04:23.154 --> 04:25.556
Do you think it should have been kept together as a unit?

04:26.357 --> 04:29.460
Well, that's been going on for many years.

04:30.521 --> 04:39.671
I had taught Bradley and Mrs. Martin and Gordon Ray, who he was very fond of.

04:39.871 --> 04:45.857
Gordon Ray was the head of the Guggenheim Foundation.

04:45.877 --> 04:48.360
And we tried.

04:48.796 --> 04:53.582
to give the collection, his bird book collection.

04:53.602 --> 04:57.026
That's probably a copy.

04:57.046 --> 04:59.349
You were saying that Bradley Martin's interest was birds.

04:59.389 --> 05:01.031
I think that was the last thing that you said.

05:01.592 --> 05:07.680
Well, his bird books were extraordinary.

05:09.802 --> 05:14.588
It was really a great, great collection.

05:14.608 --> 05:17.672
It was even suggested that there was perhaps the greatest

05:18.175 --> 05:20.478
ornithological collection anywhere.

05:20.498 --> 05:20.999
No, that's right.

05:21.339 --> 05:24.223
And that might have been an argument for keeping it as a unit.

05:24.503 --> 05:24.984
That's right.

05:25.564 --> 05:27.166
How did you personally feel about that?

05:27.206 --> 05:28.848
Did it bother you to see it broken up?

05:28.948 --> 05:35.016
Well, yes, in a way, because it'll never be put together again.

05:37.579 --> 05:44.588
And yet there's the argument on the other side that was used for Robert Ho, it was suggested for Bradley Martin,

05:45.023 --> 05:50.148
That where would the collectors of tomorrow be if people didn't allow their books to go back into the marketplace?

05:50.468 --> 05:51.169
That's true.

05:52.070 --> 05:52.690
That's true.

05:54.072 --> 05:55.553
How do you feel about that?

05:55.573 --> 06:00.378
Well, I feel that he wanted to give it away, but— That's—you think he did.

06:00.398 --> 06:03.220
He wanted—he wanted to give it away as a unit, or he wanted to— As a unit.

06:03.400 --> 06:03.721
He did?

06:04.001 --> 06:04.261
Yes.

06:07.164 --> 06:10.267
Why didn't he—he was so careful about everything else in his lifetime.

06:10.287 --> 06:11.208
Well, he was very careful.

06:11.608 --> 06:13.410
He wanted to give it to the Smithsonian.

06:15.382 --> 06:23.455
and it didn't work out.

06:25.458 --> 06:27.281
You mean he just never got around to it?

06:27.421 --> 06:29.945
No, he did go around to it.

06:29.965 --> 06:32.389
The association, they didn't handle it properly.

06:32.409 --> 06:32.770
Really?

06:34.653 --> 06:36.095
That's too bad.

06:36.275 --> 06:38.799
We went to Indiana, we thought they wanted it.

06:39.280 --> 06:40.462
Lilly, the Lilly Library?

06:40.622 --> 06:42.385
Yeah, that's quite an extraordinary library.

06:43.867 --> 06:50.314
I was there with Mrs. Martin, and it just didn't materialize.

06:51.035 --> 06:57.362
Then he got sick, you know, and he was sick for quite a time.

06:57.382 --> 07:07.793
And up to, up to, very recent, I mean, I used to see him, as I said, two or three times a week.

07:07.973 --> 07:09.655
We'd sit and talk.

07:10.141 --> 07:15.927
all the catalogs that came in, and he'd mark off, you know, show me what he ordered.

07:15.947 --> 07:18.930
We'd discuss things.

07:19.250 --> 07:20.932
Of course, he was a gentleman.

07:20.972 --> 07:22.954
He was a patrician in the truest sense.

07:23.215 --> 07:23.675
Oh, yes.

07:24.136 --> 07:30.102
But I also understand that he was very conscious of what he was paying for things, too.

07:30.182 --> 07:32.845
I mean, he did not want to overpay.

07:32.865 --> 07:33.465
Is that correct?

07:33.485 --> 07:36.248
Well, I wouldn't make that statement, no.

07:36.829 --> 07:39.051
If he wanted a thing, he'd buy it.

07:39.976 --> 07:42.079
and worry about how much it cost later.

07:44.221 --> 07:46.044
Let's go back to the beginning with yourself.

07:46.604 --> 07:54.774
Now, if you were at the wholesale in 1911 and 1912, you were just 16, 17, 18 years old.

07:56.236 --> 07:56.717
Yes, sir.

07:56.737 --> 07:59.640
When I was 13, I went to Libby's in Boston.

07:59.661 --> 08:02.184
There was an auction there.

08:03.926 --> 08:05.267
Wow.

08:05.328 --> 08:07.871
Let's start from the beginning, because I don't know very much about you.

08:07.891 --> 08:08.912
Now, are you born in New York?

08:09.373 --> 08:09.713
Yes.

08:10.655 --> 08:13.619
And how did you become fascinated with books?

08:13.980 --> 08:18.185
How did you become... Well, that's a question that I came in.

08:18.205 --> 08:20.569
You know, things happen.

08:20.589 --> 08:22.471
You have to sell books for the Salvation Army.

08:22.972 --> 08:23.873
And how old were you then?

08:24.314 --> 08:25.696
Well, I was about 12 or 13.

08:25.956 --> 08:26.357
Uh-huh.

08:26.977 --> 08:31.444
And those years when you were 12 or 13, you were a man.

08:32.625 --> 08:33.987
Today, you're 12 or 13.

08:34.948 --> 08:38.974
You're... I have grandchildren that are...

08:39.781 --> 08:43.625
Nine and ten years old, they're infants, you know.

08:43.645 --> 08:43.905
That's right.

08:43.925 --> 08:48.590
We have our daughters who are eight and seven, and, you know, they're in first and second grade.

08:48.610 --> 08:58.721
Well, you know, if you have daughters, I have nieces, but I have six grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.

08:59.702 --> 08:59.862
Wow.

09:01.464 --> 09:02.625
So, you're 12 or 13.

09:02.665 --> 09:07.009
How did you know it was books that this was going to be your interest in them?

09:07.029 --> 09:07.610
I didn't know.

09:07.630 --> 09:08.691
I made a living at it.

09:09.194 --> 09:10.717
So really, it was neat.

09:11.238 --> 09:14.445
It wasn't love, shall we say, or obsession or fascination.

09:14.465 --> 09:15.246
It wasn't love.

09:15.387 --> 09:19.395
I got into it, and I pursued it.

09:20.417 --> 09:21.780
And you went to Boston, you said?

09:21.880 --> 09:27.351
I went to Boston to a sale, and I attended every sale here in New York and in Philadelphia.

09:27.371 --> 09:27.692
Wow.

09:28.853 --> 09:32.576
Did you know a lot of these people whose libraries were disposed of?

09:33.037 --> 09:35.579
Like, for instance, let's start with the Great Hole auction, for instance.

09:35.599 --> 09:36.620
Well, I didn't know Hole.

09:36.660 --> 09:38.501
You didn't know Hole, but did you know Morgan?

09:38.681 --> 09:39.342
Did you know J.P.

09:39.382 --> 09:39.802
Morgan?

09:39.882 --> 09:41.124
Oh, yes, yeah.

09:41.184 --> 09:43.666
Tell me about him as a collector.

09:44.326 --> 09:51.312
Well, he was a— How would you compare him to Bradley Martin, shall we say, in terms of— Well, there was a difference there, you see.

09:52.333 --> 09:54.515
There was a difference in collecting.

09:55.276 --> 09:57.898
Bradley was a more cultured man.

09:59.870 --> 10:09.481
Would you say then that perhaps Morgan was closer to an accumulator than a collector?

10:09.501 --> 10:12.745
No, but he had his mind set for certain things, you see.

10:12.765 --> 10:15.347
He was a very rich man, you know.

10:15.428 --> 10:16.108
Obviously, you know.

10:16.128 --> 10:17.830
And so was Huntington, of course.

10:17.850 --> 10:19.332
So was Huntington.

10:19.352 --> 10:21.254
Huntington revolutionized book buying.

10:21.314 --> 10:23.116
He used to be bought on block.

10:23.136 --> 10:23.597
On block.

10:23.657 --> 10:25.759
The phrase came in with him, didn't it?

10:25.779 --> 10:26.200
That's right.

10:26.300 --> 10:29.083
So within four or five years, he was able to put together

10:29.755 --> 10:30.656
He bought everything.

10:31.056 --> 10:31.457
Everything.

10:33.399 --> 10:36.723
And did you ever meet any of these people, Huntington or Morgan?

10:37.243 --> 10:42.309
No, I've met Morgan's brother, Henry Morgan.

10:43.109 --> 10:49.096
I had some letters from him, yeah.

10:49.116 --> 10:51.038
But the other collectors I knew as well.

10:53.000 --> 10:55.763
Who would you say are some of the great collectors alive today?

10:57.076 --> 11:00.259
Do they compare with the collectors of the Golden Age?

11:00.640 --> 11:01.360
Well, I wouldn't know.

11:01.801 --> 11:06.426
Dealers had certain, you know.

11:06.446 --> 11:10.390
Well, from what you can see, I mean, this Richard Manny, for instance, who bought the Shakespeare's.

11:10.790 --> 11:11.791
Yeah, yeah.

11:11.811 --> 11:13.573
I guess he's moving pretty quickly, isn't he?

11:13.593 --> 11:15.195
He's moving very heavily, thank you.

11:15.375 --> 11:15.715
Two million.

11:15.735 --> 11:16.196
Two million.

11:16.276 --> 11:17.617
That's right.

11:17.637 --> 11:18.278
1.9 plus the, you know.

11:18.318 --> 11:19.539
Plus the commission.

11:19.559 --> 11:21.061
The commission, yeah.

11:21.822 --> 11:24.404
I mean, he was sitting right next to me at the sale when he bought it.

11:25.125 --> 11:25.506
He was?

11:25.726 --> 11:25.986
Yeah.

11:26.236 --> 11:26.997
What were you thinking?

11:27.037 --> 11:28.679
I mean, they were going up for $50,000 pops.

11:30.221 --> 11:31.342
He has a dealer.

11:31.362 --> 11:32.404
Jim Cummins.

11:32.424 --> 11:33.044
Jim Cummins.

11:33.705 --> 11:37.610
Jim was sitting next to me, and he was sitting right next to Jim.

11:38.251 --> 11:41.695
And he'd tell him, go ahead, Jim.

11:41.715 --> 11:42.936
What was going through your mind?

11:42.956 --> 11:47.522
Now, you were at the wholesale where the Gutenberg Bible sold for $50,000.

11:47.682 --> 11:51.807
And that was considered the greatest, the most, the greatest thing that ever happened.

11:51.827 --> 11:53.529
And that price stood for years and years.

11:53.670 --> 11:54.050
That's right.

11:54.070 --> 11:55.652
And here, you're at an auction.

11:55.987 --> 11:58.409
where the increments are $50,000.

11:59.010 --> 12:02.833
I mean, what do you think when you see what has happened in your lifetime?

12:02.853 --> 12:03.554
I can't think.

12:04.235 --> 12:10.400
I sold things to people where they come up at auction and they bring 40 to 50 times.

12:13.643 --> 12:15.125
What they bought them for.

12:15.285 --> 12:15.605
Yeah.

12:16.145 --> 12:17.847
What you sold them for.

12:17.867 --> 12:20.129
Sure.

12:20.149 --> 12:20.930
I could prove it.

12:21.110 --> 12:24.373
I could give you examples of things that

12:24.775 --> 12:36.908
Well, that went for three million.

12:36.968 --> 12:38.970
How much?

12:38.990 --> 12:41.893
Didn't the Japanese buy it for three million or something like that?

12:41.913 --> 12:42.353
No, no.

12:42.794 --> 12:45.997
Three million nine hundred dollars, almost four million dollars.

12:46.918 --> 12:48.300
Twenty-nine thousand dollars.

12:49.381 --> 12:50.462
My God, you're so confused.

12:51.623 --> 12:53.125
And it was a perfect copy, too.

12:53.165 --> 12:56.069
The finest copy I've ever seen.

12:56.089 --> 12:59.294
Did he request that particular copy from you?

12:59.314 --> 13:01.197
Did he ask you to purchase that copy for him?

13:01.217 --> 13:03.180
Yeah, that particular copy she's asking.

13:03.420 --> 13:04.442
That particular copy?

13:04.482 --> 13:06.084
No, not that particular copy.

13:06.484 --> 13:09.950
He sent me to Philadelphia to look at a copy.

13:11.432 --> 13:14.196
And I went there, spent all day, and I came back.

13:14.917 --> 13:17.681
He was living at that time on a certain place.

13:18.422 --> 13:20.685
And I said, Bradley, this is not your...

13:21.188 --> 13:29.597
This is not your quality, because when you turned the pages, they were torn, and they were spotted.

13:29.617 --> 13:33.301
And I said, look, there's one in London I could buy for $29,000.

13:33.381 --> 13:35.624
Let me buy that one for you.

13:35.644 --> 13:36.585
So I ordered it.

13:36.605 --> 13:37.246
So he said, fine.

13:37.606 --> 13:37.786
Sure.

13:38.427 --> 13:40.469
How much was the one in Philadelphia going for?

13:40.489 --> 13:40.950
$21,000.

13:41.310 --> 13:43.612
So we're talking $8,000.

13:43.632 --> 13:46.155
But $8,000 was a lot of money in those days.

13:46.876 --> 13:48.698
But he wanted the perfect copy.

13:50.467 --> 13:51.528
And look what it went for.

13:53.049 --> 13:54.371
Any other examples like that?

13:54.411 --> 14:02.458
That's quite an extraordinary... No, I mean, there are lots of things that he bought.

14:06.802 --> 14:08.944
Actually, I can get that stuff out of the catalog.

14:08.964 --> 14:10.406
I think that's in the catalog.

14:10.626 --> 14:11.987
I have the catalogs at home.

14:12.067 --> 14:14.610
Well, there's a new catalog that's going to be out now.

14:15.090 --> 14:17.012
I wrote the introduction to this.

14:17.032 --> 14:18.313
Oh, really?

14:18.783 --> 14:20.966
For the one that's coming down in a couple weeks?

14:20.986 --> 14:23.148
Or the one that's coming down at the end of January?

14:23.208 --> 14:24.290
That's right.

14:24.310 --> 14:25.812
The big one, the Americano one?

14:25.832 --> 14:26.072
Yeah.

14:26.272 --> 14:28.955
Oh, that's supposed to be a wonderful auction.

14:28.975 --> 14:29.076
Yeah.

14:29.096 --> 14:29.997
I'm going to come to that.

14:30.037 --> 14:31.498
I'm going to seek you out.

14:31.579 --> 14:33.100
I might even sit near you.

14:33.221 --> 14:36.344
Come on, sit with me.

14:36.364 --> 14:37.526
So you haven't missed any of them?

14:38.287 --> 14:38.547
No.

14:39.388 --> 14:40.529
Did you know Jerome Curran?

14:41.130 --> 14:44.935
No, I knew him well and knew his lawyer.

14:45.055 --> 14:47.558
How do you explain a collector like Curran?

14:48.230 --> 14:53.196
I guess what I'm driving at is because he decided to give everything up, to get rid of everything.

14:54.217 --> 15:01.166
Well, things were at that peak, you know, and he sold everything.

15:02.047 --> 15:06.393
And then he went in again for collecting.

15:06.413 --> 15:07.274
It wasn't the same.

15:07.854 --> 15:17.106
Do you think that he typifies a lot of the kind of collector who the drive is to acquire?

15:17.508 --> 15:20.031
And once you have it, you almost lose interest in it?

15:20.271 --> 15:23.155
I had a customer that came in years ago, 1929.

15:23.836 --> 15:32.887
I got him interested and walked with me, Charles Feinberg.

15:32.907 --> 15:34.709
And he just died.

15:34.729 --> 15:38.454
He gave his whole collection to the Library of Congress.

15:39.315 --> 15:40.216
I know that, yeah.

15:40.416 --> 15:40.717
What?

15:40.737 --> 15:41.518
I've heard that.

15:42.519 --> 15:44.882
He was your customer?

15:46.263 --> 15:50.327
There wasn't a day in the week that he didn't talk to me, you know.

15:50.347 --> 15:53.990
I'd buy all this stuff for him.

15:54.010 --> 15:54.971
I'd buy it everywhere.

15:57.313 --> 15:59.515
Did you get him the first Leaves of Grass?

15:59.955 --> 16:00.656
Yeah.

16:00.796 --> 16:04.439
That's one of the toughest American books there is to get.

16:04.459 --> 16:05.881
There's been dozens around.

16:05.901 --> 16:06.801
Bradley has one.

16:08.163 --> 16:12.106
We're talking about a book that's probably going to go for $150,000, $200,000, maybe more.

16:12.266 --> 16:13.948
Leaves of Grass?

16:14.128 --> 16:14.228
Yeah.

16:14.950 --> 16:17.793
The first one now, the privately printed one.

16:17.813 --> 16:18.614
1855.

16:18.734 --> 16:18.934
Right.

16:19.174 --> 16:20.576
That's right.

16:20.996 --> 16:23.398
Well, how much do you think that's going to go for in fine condition?

16:23.418 --> 16:25.340
$25,000.

16:25.440 --> 16:27.963
That's all.

16:27.983 --> 16:30.365
I thought that would command more than that.

16:33.869 --> 16:40.295
I lost my ... Well, would you say that Kern was buying as an investor or as a collector?

16:41.276 --> 16:42.617
He was buying as a collector.

16:42.637 --> 16:43.438
He was buying both.

16:45.511 --> 16:51.765
What do you think of people who buy for investment purposes as opposed to... Oh, that's a gamble you're taking.

16:52.246 --> 16:55.332
That's a pure gamble you're taking, you know.

16:56.274 --> 16:58.219
I mean, but what do you think of people who do that?

16:58.680 --> 17:01.065
I don't bother with people like that.

17:01.085 --> 17:02.929
If you want to buy for an investment, that's it.

17:02.949 --> 17:03.891
You're down on Wall Street.

17:07.364 --> 17:29.088
We're talking about the difference between the person who buys, say, a Van Gogh for $40,000 or $50,000 million.

17:29.128 --> 17:33.172
The difference between the art collector and the book collector.

17:33.473 --> 17:34.353
There is no debt deal.

17:34.394 --> 17:35.615
You can't.

17:35.635 --> 17:36.696
They're two different things.

17:38.600 --> 17:40.342
Are they two different kinds of collector?

17:40.402 --> 17:42.443
They're two different kinds of collector.

17:42.583 --> 17:43.965
How would you describe the difference?

17:44.185 --> 17:49.810
Well, for instance, I had a customer whose name was Sang, Phil Sang, in Chicago.

17:52.232 --> 17:57.817
He started buying small things, you know, signatures and so on.

17:57.837 --> 18:04.543
Turned out to be one of the great collectors of autographs.

18:04.563 --> 18:06.605
He had a sale that brought over a million.

18:07.545 --> 18:08.286
S-A-N-G?

18:08.536 --> 18:14.381
Yes.

18:14.401 --> 18:18.505
And the point being compared, like, to art, though, the painting?

18:18.525 --> 18:21.728
No, you see, you can't compare that.

18:21.748 --> 18:26.313
I mean, you can't compare a man that buys a picture that wants to hang up on the wall.

18:26.733 --> 18:27.334
It's an ornament.

18:27.714 --> 18:37.463
It's an ornament to a man who wants to buy a letter because he was a great man, you know, because he was

18:39.974 --> 18:41.356
He gave something to the lawyer.

18:41.376 --> 18:44.781
I see what you're saying.

18:44.801 --> 18:50.389
One of the ironies, I think, of the book or manuscript collector is that you buy these things and you really can never touch them.

18:50.509 --> 18:54.014
I mean, you leave, you don't display them, shall we say.

18:54.454 --> 18:54.895
That's right.

18:56.017 --> 19:00.022
And in many cases, you'll find the book collector is very private.

19:00.042 --> 19:02.406
He doesn't even want anybody to know that he owns these things.

19:02.946 --> 19:07.072
Whereas the owner of a great painting, everybody just walks into the house, looks at it.

19:07.192 --> 19:07.753
Looks at it.

19:09.320 --> 19:10.241
Now, how about yourself?

19:10.281 --> 19:11.363
Have you ever been a collector?

19:12.204 --> 19:15.770
I was interested in folklore myself.

19:16.251 --> 19:17.953
I had a little collection, which I sold.

19:18.134 --> 19:19.916
I mean, you know, it was getting beyond me.

19:20.237 --> 19:24.183
I was too busy in the business, and I was traveling all over the world.

19:24.203 --> 19:31.855
I used to go to Europe five, six, seven, eight times a year, ten times a year sometimes.

19:31.875 --> 19:32.476
To buy books?

19:32.876 --> 19:34.118
Yeah.

19:34.138 --> 19:36.482
Did you buy from estates, or you went to auctions?

19:36.502 --> 19:37.183
I went to auctions.

19:38.918 --> 19:40.280
Do you like buying at auction?

19:41.501 --> 19:46.427
I was a very heavy buyer at auction years ago, very heavy.

19:46.467 --> 19:48.490
What kind of instincts do you work with?

19:50.272 --> 19:53.256
It's something that you know.

19:53.336 --> 20:00.825
You have clients and you think that this man ought to be interested in that.

20:00.845 --> 20:03.929
So you buy it or buy it for him.

20:03.949 --> 20:08.014
Do you buy often just on speculation with the thought?

20:08.787 --> 20:10.108
That you might have a client?

20:10.128 --> 20:12.892
Of course you are, of course, of course.

20:12.912 --> 20:19.058
I mean, let's say that you were bidding on the Shakespeare's, and Manny wasn't there with you.

20:19.078 --> 20:22.682
I don't know whether I would have gone that high.

20:22.702 --> 20:23.263
I don't know.

20:23.283 --> 20:25.526
I mean, that's a lot of money for the Shakespeare's.

20:25.546 --> 20:26.126
That's a lot of money.

20:26.166 --> 20:28.269
Because Shakespeare is as wonderful as they are.

20:28.329 --> 20:29.190
They're not rare books.

20:29.210 --> 20:36.658
There was one a year ago, was sold for $600 and some odd thousand dollars.

20:36.678 --> 20:37.579
This very set.

20:38.065 --> 20:39.587
Crouse had it last.

20:39.667 --> 20:41.310
I called it Crouse.

20:41.330 --> 20:44.975
And they had it listed in their catalog just 15 years ago for $165,000.

20:44.995 --> 20:45.937
There you go.

20:46.057 --> 20:49.382
And the thing went up to $2 million.

20:49.582 --> 20:51.866
You know, I mean, how can you explain things?

20:52.206 --> 20:54.690
It's very difficult.

20:54.710 --> 20:57.655
And yet, how high do you... I don't know.

20:57.975 --> 20:58.436
I don't know.

20:59.217 --> 21:03.263
It all depends how well you're in with your clients.

21:04.778 --> 21:07.662
And it helps that the client's there with you, too, doesn't it?

21:07.682 --> 21:10.967
It helps that the client's there with you.

21:10.987 --> 21:13.230
You answered the question.

21:13.250 --> 21:21.662
But have you ever gone to any of these auctions where they don't... The client doesn't really want the competition to know who he is, who's buying it.

21:21.682 --> 21:22.083
Oh, yes.

21:22.143 --> 21:26.048
Lots of people don't want their names mentioned.

21:26.068 --> 21:28.091
Nicholas Barker, you know Nicholas Barker?

21:28.151 --> 21:31.176
I did an interview with him a few weeks ago from the British Library.

21:32.077 --> 21:32.197
Yeah.

21:32.217 --> 21:32.878
He said...

21:33.145 --> 21:42.277
He feels that you can really tell the climate of the market more by the underbidder than the one who gets the prize.

21:43.899 --> 21:49.046
In other words, we don't know how high Manny would have been willing to go to get those Shakespeare's.

21:49.106 --> 21:51.589
I don't think he would have gone any higher.

21:52.170 --> 21:52.811
He quit, right?

21:52.831 --> 21:53.872
Because he hesitated.

21:53.952 --> 21:55.915
Remember John said, think about it?

21:56.095 --> 21:58.278
I was sitting right there, man.

21:59.079 --> 22:02.123
I was sitting as close to him, closer than I'm sitting to you.

22:02.609 --> 22:04.692
And I heard the conversation going on.

22:04.712 --> 22:05.493
What were they saying?

22:06.194 --> 22:08.357
You know, you just go ahead, you know.

22:08.377 --> 22:09.699
Yeah, but he told them to think about it.

22:09.779 --> 22:13.924
He was ready to— And he put his hand up, you know, and— And that was that.

22:15.867 --> 22:18.431
So, in other words, this was it, two million, and then I'm out.

22:18.691 --> 22:20.053
I wonder who he was bidding against.

22:20.073 --> 22:22.096
That would be nice to know who the competition was.

22:22.256 --> 22:22.917
Well, I don't know.

22:23.037 --> 22:23.858
Dr. Gallery could tell you.

22:24.091 --> 22:30.638
It was a telephone bidder, but it was... Maybe a telephone bid, I don't know.

22:30.658 --> 22:31.959
Yeah, but Quaritch wasn't in that.

22:32.019 --> 22:33.961
Quaritch was buying pretty much everything else.

22:34.082 --> 22:36.144
He was buying a lot of stuff, Quaritch.

22:36.304 --> 22:41.149
Yeah, he got the Cervantes for, I'm told, for a Spanish collector, is what I heard.

22:41.169 --> 22:43.612
Yeah, you buy for people, you know, like I used to do.

22:44.713 --> 22:51.600
But you see, I'm not so heavy in buying today, because at my age,

22:52.694 --> 22:55.598
I just hang on with a few people.

22:57.301 --> 22:57.401
Yeah.

22:57.982 --> 23:04.191
But I hear the book Grapevine out there that you're still pretty well involved in this.

23:04.331 --> 23:05.453
Of course I'm involved.

23:05.513 --> 23:06.635
I'm always involved.

23:07.095 --> 23:10.340
I'm involved all the time, and I will always be involved.

23:11.822 --> 23:14.927
I'm told you know where all the great books are, all the great pages.

23:14.967 --> 23:15.267
That's right.

23:15.327 --> 23:21.857
I know where a lot of the books are, and I know where collections that I've made that would give it away to institutions.

23:22.816 --> 23:27.022
Well, that must be satisfying to some degree.

23:27.903 --> 23:28.203
You know?

23:28.524 --> 23:32.810
Like, for instance, which collections have been given to institutions that you can think of offhand?

23:32.850 --> 23:36.014
Well, a man by the name of Hugh Peele gave this whole collection.

23:36.034 --> 23:36.675
Famous, yeah.

23:36.695 --> 23:38.858
Yeah, gave this whole collection, you know, it's in Kentucky.

23:39.199 --> 23:40.340
That's a famous collection.

23:40.661 --> 23:40.761
Sure.

23:40.901 --> 23:42.002
You built that collection?

23:43.865 --> 23:43.965
Yeah.

23:43.985 --> 23:46.889
These are very famous collections he's mentioning.

23:46.909 --> 23:48.271
I haven't had all of them.

23:48.471 --> 23:51.135
Great collection of Charles and Mary Lamb.

23:51.807 --> 23:52.308
Oh, my.

23:52.368 --> 23:54.050
Was that original manuscript style?

23:54.070 --> 23:54.451
Yeah, that's right.

23:55.412 --> 23:56.193
And where did that go?

23:56.233 --> 24:00.559
That went to Kentucky.

24:00.579 --> 24:00.779
Yeah.

24:01.641 --> 24:06.888
Do you kind of have mixed emotions when you see it go to an institution, and then you know it's never going to be offered again?

24:06.908 --> 24:07.489
Of course.

24:08.150 --> 24:11.574
Because as a dealer, you might like to say, geez, I'd like to have another whack at that.

24:11.935 --> 24:13.277
Well, you may or may not.

24:13.357 --> 24:16.261
I mean, all the things you see.

24:16.281 --> 24:20.667
You see, the market has changed so dramatically, so dramatically.

24:22.604 --> 24:29.416
in the last five years, that sometimes I don't recognize what's going on.

24:29.436 --> 24:30.878
Talk to me a little bit about that.

24:30.898 --> 24:32.461
How has it changed, not just the money?

24:32.561 --> 24:34.645
Are you talking just in terms of the value, or...?

24:34.845 --> 24:38.191
I'm talking about money value, dollar-wise.

24:39.693 --> 24:41.997
But the institutions aren't buying as much.

24:42.498 --> 24:47.667
It's the private collector who's... Well, the private collector has more money than he ever had before.

24:48.001 --> 24:50.203
And the institutions don't have what they used to have.

24:50.303 --> 24:54.167
And the institutions don't have what they used to have.

24:54.227 --> 24:55.928
That's about the nutshell of it, right there.

24:55.948 --> 24:57.149
That's the whole thing, right there.

24:58.250 --> 24:59.451
That's what I wrote for this Sunday.

24:59.491 --> 25:05.757
That's the essence of what I said, is that David Redden feels that we're in a new golden age of book collecting.

25:05.777 --> 25:06.678
Would you agree with that?

25:09.760 --> 25:12.763
Well, yes and no.

25:14.324 --> 25:17.147
Don't forget you don't have as many

25:17.397 --> 25:19.400
book sales as there were years ago.

25:22.784 --> 25:28.492
And the money is freer.

25:29.753 --> 25:30.074
Today?

25:30.394 --> 25:30.674
Yeah.

25:31.395 --> 25:32.577
What do you mean freer, looser?

25:32.957 --> 25:36.722
Looser, I mean, people are willing to throw it around.

25:36.943 --> 25:38.324
People are willing to, that's right.

25:38.905 --> 25:40.327
You think that, I mean, is that correct?

25:40.347 --> 25:41.328
Is that a correct assumption?

25:41.348 --> 25:43.051
That's right.

25:43.071 --> 25:43.331
That's right.

25:43.351 --> 25:44.873
And you say it amazes you to see it.

25:45.241 --> 25:58.258
It amazes me to see it because being in the business for the many years that I've been in, sometimes it was hard to sell a client, you know, and he's got to figure out where the money is going to come from, you know.

25:58.298 --> 25:59.900
But today it seems to be.

26:02.844 --> 26:06.930
Do you find, now my regular job is I'm a book review editor.

26:07.130 --> 26:10.074
I'm the book review editor of the Worcester Telegram in Massachusetts.

26:10.254 --> 26:11.055
Oh.

26:11.075 --> 26:12.036
And I review books.

26:12.096 --> 26:14.860
I'm a critic as well as a writer of collecting.

26:15.548 --> 26:23.516
And I find, and the reason I say this is that I find, having done this for 12 years now, that when I get, I feel that I know people.

26:25.218 --> 26:25.658
You're just a baby.

26:25.678 --> 26:26.379
That's nice to hear.

26:26.399 --> 26:27.660
You're just an infant.

26:27.681 --> 26:30.844
You're an infant.

26:30.864 --> 26:32.065
You've made my day.

26:32.866 --> 26:38.291
I feel that to know a person is to know their reading habits.

26:38.452 --> 26:39.172
Well, of course.

26:39.192 --> 26:41.915
And do you feel the same way as a book dealer?

26:41.935 --> 26:42.356
That's right.

26:42.976 --> 26:44.678
I mean, that almost, that you can almost,

26:45.367 --> 26:48.570
consider yourself something of a psychiatrist.

26:48.790 --> 26:50.471
That's perhaps a little too strong.

26:50.632 --> 26:52.513
That's a little bit too strong, you know.

26:52.653 --> 26:53.974
But a confidant, certainly.

26:54.195 --> 26:55.716
That's different.

26:55.936 --> 27:00.040
You have a window into the person's... See, let me give you an example.

27:01.361 --> 27:04.704
I've got it right here, which I'm working on now.

27:04.724 --> 27:05.084
Wonderful.

27:05.104 --> 27:08.247
There was a man by the name of Litauer.

27:11.469 --> 27:12.891
That name's familiar for some reason.

27:13.611 --> 27:14.412
And he was...

27:15.286 --> 27:24.117
He was a taught riding, horse riding, at a big place in Long Island.

27:26.360 --> 27:27.601
Known all over the world.

27:29.644 --> 27:35.491
You know, his riding, teaching people how to saddle and ride a horse.

27:35.511 --> 27:36.292
Austrian arts.

27:36.653 --> 27:37.153
That's right.

27:39.736 --> 27:43.581
I met him about, oh, I don't know, 30, 40 years ago.

27:44.542 --> 27:45.023
He died.

27:46.100 --> 27:49.309
And you see, here is this collection which I have to appraise.

27:52.940 --> 28:00.582
And he's got books from the

28:18.770 --> 28:21.633
He's got books from the 15th century.

28:22.013 --> 28:23.695
Wow, 15th century.

28:26.438 --> 28:28.340
These are even pre-incunibles, aren't they?

28:28.400 --> 28:29.642
I mean, incunibles.

28:29.702 --> 28:37.610
1632, 1623, 1685, 1619.

28:38.010 --> 28:41.654
Then he goes on.

28:41.995 --> 28:43.356
So this fellow's name is Liddauer?

28:43.596 --> 28:43.897
Yeah.

28:43.997 --> 28:44.657
Is he an American?

28:46.119 --> 28:47.140
Or did he say British?

28:47.812 --> 28:51.176
I don't know what he was, but he wasn't, he was a poet.

28:52.998 --> 29:05.892
And then he's got... And then he's got the modern books, you know.

29:07.394 --> 29:11.899
So he really covers the subject.

29:11.919 --> 29:13.521
Yeah.

29:13.541 --> 29:15.203
Now, are you appraising this?

29:15.723 --> 29:16.664
For the estate.

29:16.684 --> 29:19.848
For the estate, which probably intends to put it up for auction, is that?

29:20.128 --> 29:22.010
No, I don't know what she's going to do.

29:22.371 --> 29:23.712
I spoke to Mrs. Liddow.

29:25.314 --> 29:32.182
This is interesting, and I'm not talking about the, and this is not with respect to the Liddowers, or anyone specifically.

29:32.202 --> 29:36.127
There's a collection of books that I have to do on the Vietnam War.

29:36.768 --> 29:38.469
That's a very interesting subject now.

29:38.490 --> 29:38.750
See?

29:39.871 --> 29:42.274
See?

29:42.294 --> 29:43.636
Only on the Vietnam War.

29:43.896 --> 29:44.937
How do you appraise these?

29:45.642 --> 29:47.264
When there really isn't a bibliography.

29:47.704 --> 29:59.339
There is a bibliography, but most of these are out of print, and you kind of put a, you know, you get a feeling of what a book is worth, and you put a price on it, and a collection.

29:59.599 --> 30:02.222
You could put a bigger price than an individual book.

30:02.903 --> 30:03.864
Because it's a collection.

30:04.024 --> 30:05.246
Because it's a collection.

30:05.266 --> 30:07.909
Because it's the easy way to get the whole thing fast.

30:09.491 --> 30:13.776
If you've got all of Dickens, all of Dickens is worth more than

30:14.043 --> 30:16.626
than all of Dickens in individual segments.

30:18.208 --> 30:19.710
Probably twice, actually.

30:19.730 --> 30:23.075
Isn't that what the figure is, generally, sometimes?

30:23.795 --> 30:25.117
How about taste and fashion?

30:25.958 --> 30:27.500
You say you've seen the market change.

30:27.560 --> 30:29.923
How about taste and fashion in book collecting?

30:30.384 --> 30:31.445
Have you seen that change?

30:31.746 --> 30:32.987
Yes, it changes.

30:33.007 --> 30:34.069
Sure, that changes.

30:35.510 --> 30:43.020
At one time, a North, you couldn't sell a North, but all of a sudden,

30:43.439 --> 30:48.206
something happened and the world runs and tries to buy it.

30:49.808 --> 30:52.552
Well, Melville was like that for the longest time, wasn't he?

30:52.572 --> 30:55.657
Well, I sold Bradley Melville's Bible.

30:57.239 --> 30:57.880
God, he used.

30:58.802 --> 31:04.510
He's got a little story that just popped out, didn't he?

31:06.052 --> 31:08.596
Coming up at sale, I think.

31:08.656 --> 31:10.759
Now, where did you find Melville's Bible?

31:11.080 --> 31:13.243
I found it in Joliet, Illinois.

31:15.080 --> 31:16.222
And how did you get wind of it?

31:16.242 --> 31:27.837
Well, a customer of mine who was an autograph collector came to his house one night, and there I saw this and some other medical things, and I bought them all and I sold them to Brasley.

31:27.957 --> 31:29.900
Did he know what he had, the guy?

31:29.920 --> 31:33.504
Oh, sure, sure.

31:33.524 --> 31:36.308
You must have a million stories about extraordinary finds.

31:36.569 --> 31:39.052
Oh, yes, I have a million stories.

31:40.614 --> 31:42.977
I was going to look for a list here.

31:44.054 --> 31:45.877
I suppose this is in another file.

31:47.259 --> 31:51.765
I gave Bradley a list of the library that I bought.

31:51.785 --> 31:54.409
He was sitting where you're sitting.

31:54.429 --> 31:58.414
And he went through it, and he used to mark H-B-N.

31:58.474 --> 32:00.778
He marked it H-B-N.

32:01.999 --> 32:04.884
And he marked it on the edge, H-B-N, H-B-N.

32:05.384 --> 32:07.247
When I brought the library in... Very easy, wasn't it?

32:07.688 --> 32:07.928
Yes.

32:08.509 --> 32:10.872
When I brought the library in, there were eight or ten

32:11.678 --> 32:15.243
part of the whole group, you know, that had his mark.

32:15.263 --> 32:16.765
And I put him in front of him.

32:17.246 --> 32:22.152
It came to 18,000-something, I don't remember the exact amount.

32:22.172 --> 32:25.517
And he took his wallet out and he wrote a check out.

32:25.817 --> 32:27.840
And they carried him out?

32:28.120 --> 32:29.362
Yeah.

32:29.422 --> 32:30.323
Did he love books?

32:30.383 --> 32:31.084
He loved books.

32:31.124 --> 32:35.731
Did something happen to him when he, I mean, that you could see when he came in contact with a great book?

32:35.751 --> 32:36.311
He loved books.

32:37.673 --> 32:38.935
I guess I'm looking for

32:39.286 --> 32:47.358
some kind of insight into what it is that really transforms a person into what we call bibliomaniacs.

32:48.039 --> 32:49.441
Do you have any thoughts on that?

32:50.323 --> 32:52.125
I'm not a physician.

32:52.206 --> 32:52.746
I don't know.

32:52.867 --> 32:54.509
I'm not a psychiatrist.

32:55.070 --> 32:58.715
I don't know what can... But motivation, I guess, is what I mean.

32:58.735 --> 33:02.701
You must have some sense as to what motivates people to do this.

33:02.721 --> 33:06.407
Well, it's a thing that...

33:06.961 --> 33:08.523
It's a lot for a thing, you know.

33:08.643 --> 33:12.567
You start with one, then you get two, then you get three, then you get four.

33:12.587 --> 33:17.172
And you say, well, I'll add to it to see myself.

33:17.192 --> 33:20.456
Yeah, but for instance, now you're talking about the equestrian collection.

33:21.037 --> 33:22.658
Here's the wife having it appraised.

33:23.599 --> 33:28.885
She, I would imagine, didn't share the same enthusiasm for the subject as the husband did.

33:28.905 --> 33:31.348
Of course not.

33:31.700 --> 33:42.314
Well, that was his profession, his occupation, but Bradley certainly wasn't a bird, he wasn't an ornithological of what, how do you put it?

33:42.334 --> 33:46.840
He wasn't a bird specialist, yet he loved books about birds, you know, finest collections.

33:46.901 --> 33:49.744
Well, he started with reading W.H.

33:50.525 --> 34:00.559
Hudson, you know, as a naturalist, and he pulled out a book, and with that we started, and it just went on and on and on.

34:00.927 --> 34:03.210
There'll never be another collection like it.

34:03.851 --> 34:06.915
That is a shame.

